Subject: [PATCH 23/28] =?UTF-8?q?inline-3d(#625):=20GPU-process=20SYNCHRON?=
 =?UTF-8?q?OUS=20weave=20=E2=80=94=20zero-lag,=20browser-owned?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Runs the OpenXR present-owner weave session INSIDE the GPU process (created in
gpu_main.cc PreSandboxStartup, before LowerToken()), so per-frame
xrWeaveSubmitDXR is a synchronous in-process call on Viz's present thread — no
mojo, no browser hop, no sync_call_restrictions deadlock. Viz composite → weave
→ draw-back happens in ONE frame, eliminating the ~1-frame async round-trip
floor. User-eyeballed: woven inline-3D on the demo gallery, scroll lag greatly
reduced.

Opt-in behind --inline-3d-sync-weave (the default --enable-inline-3d async mojo
path is untouched as a fallback):
- gpu_main.cc: PreSandboxStartup hook (gated) connects the runtime IPC pipe +
  creates the window-bound present-owner session pre-sandbox (the sandbox blocks
  OPENING the pipe, not I/O on the open handle). IsInline3DGpuProcess() excludes
  the info-collection GPU process.
- DisplayXRWeaveClient: PreSandboxInitializeForGpuProcess() (session create,
  bindWindow, process-DACL widen so the Medium service can dup the woven handle
  back into the Low GPU process). Submit() gains input_is_dxgi. Browser-process
  session suppressed under the sync flag so the two don't race on the pipe.
- DisplayXRWeaveGpu: SyncMode() routes to a direct synchronous Submit and stores
  the woven result immediately, so Viz's existing same-frame TryTakeWovenResult
  draws it back with zero lag (WeaveCompositedSurface is UNCHANGED). The input is
  a LEGACY DXGI keyed-mutex handle (tagged over the runtime IPC — a Low-integrity
  GPU process can't OpenProcess the Medium service to send an NT handle).
- weave_client is now a component() (COMPONENT_EXPORT) so its process-global
  session State() is a SINGLE instance across DLLs (content.dll pre-sandbox init
  + components_viz_service.dll per-frame submit); a source_set duplicated it.

Requires the runtime IPC fixes (displayxr-runtime#743): Low-integrity pipe
label, mainloop mid-connect-abort hardening, tagged-handle transport.
